ONYX COFFEE REPORT

My thoughts this month about Onyx were spurred by an article about digital surveillance by ZoÃ« Hitzig. This quote in particular:

 

In her 2015 book In Defense of Secrets, the late French psychoanalyst Anne Dufourmantelle corrects one of the implicit claims of the surveillance-as-intimacy perspective: â€œTransparency is not truth,â€ she writes.

 

The essay as a whole argues that big tech has hoodwinked us into seeing surveillance â€œas a form of intimacy.â€ Being on someoneâ€™s Find My is a badge of closeness; BeReal catches us in candid moments. However, â€œthe sense that we are showing less filtered and more continuous footage of our lives to our friends distracts us from the reality that we are also showing all of it to the extraordinarily powerful tech companies that gave us the idea to do so in the first place.â€

 

The transparency-is-not-truth quote comes as Hitzig considers how unmediated digital access to friends and partnersâ€™ lives can warp these relationships. Surveillance leaves no opportunity for trust or to see each other as autonomous individuals with the right to secrets! The â€œtrueâ€ friend is not the one you know everything about: where theyâ€™ve been, who theyâ€™ve talked to, etc. The â€œtrueâ€ friend is the one right in front of you, whose depths you can never fully know.

 

Onyx Coffee Lab prides themselves on being transparent. One place this manifests is their price breakdowns. They publish how much they paid for a coffee, how much went to shipping, importers, and roasting. Another site of transparency, though, is their packaging. Each coffee or tea box has a paragraph long description of its origin. The question I am asking is: in the face of all this information, where is the truth? Or is this just a surveillance logic calculated to generate yet another faux intimacy?  

 

